Overcoming distrust



Despite such sentiments, there is lingering scepticism as well as distrust over the way in which the Zimbabwean government has handled the pandemic. There is also a perceived lack of transparency over the procurement of the vaccines.



The Media Institute of Southern Africa’s Zimbabwe chapter won a high court order in February compelling the government to release comprehensive information to the public on the spread and management of Covid-19 following concerns that it was not doing enough in this regard.



Speaking after the country had received the first batch of Sinopharm vaccines, Tabani Moyo, the institute’s director, said his organisation remained worried about the lack of access to information on the Covid-19 management programme, including the vaccination strategy.



“What the government has simply said is that we are going to do intense analyses of the drugs. How do you procure and start to investigate when you have already procured? It does not make sense that you go all the way in terms of logistical costs and get a drug and you say you want to start analysing it. This is quite worrying and we hope that medical professionals will be given the scope and space to take a frontline role rather than politicians,” Moyo said.



<img data-attachment-id="122194" data-permalink="https://www.newframe.com/slow-start-to-zimbabwes-vaccination-campaign/8mar_zim-vaccines_km006/" data-orig-file="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/8Mar_Zim-Vaccines_KM006-scaled.jpg" data-orig-size="2560,1707" data-comments-opened="0" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;4&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;ILCE-7M2&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;24 February 2021: Dr Edwin Sibanda, the City of Bulawayo\u2019s Director of Health services, was the first person to get vaccinated at North End Clinic.&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;1614161134&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;24&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;640&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0.025&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="8Mar_Zim-Vaccines_KM006" data-image-description="" data-medium-file="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/8Mar_Zim-Vaccines_KM006-960x640.jpg" data-large-file="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/8Mar_Zim-Vaccines_KM006-1440x960.jpg" loading="lazy" width="2560" height="1707" src="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/8Mar_Zim-Vaccines_KM006-scaled.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-122194" srcset="https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/8Mar_Zim-Vaccines_KM006-scaled.jpg 2560w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/8Mar_Zim-Vaccines_KM006-960x640.jpg 960w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/8Mar_Zim-Vaccines_KM006-1440x960.jpg 1440w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/8Mar_Zim-Vaccines_KM006-768x512.jpg 768w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/8Mar_Zim-Vaccines_KM006-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/8Mar_Zim-Vaccines_KM006-2048x1365.jpg 2048w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/8Mar_Zim-Vaccines_KM006-1920x1280.jpg 1920w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/8Mar_Zim-Vaccines_KM006-480x320.jpg 480w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/8Mar_Zim-Vaccines_KM006-270x180.jpg 270w, https://www.newframe.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/8Mar_Zim-Vaccines_KM006-560x373.jpg 560w" sizes="(max-width: 2560px) 100vw, 2560px" />24 February 2021: Edwin Sibanda, Bulawayo’s director of health services, was the first person to get vaccinated at the Northern Suburbs Clinic.



Correct information



Physician and former health minister Henry Madzorera said Zimbabweans had every reason to be concerned and could be excused for being cynical about the vaccines as well as the inoculation programme because the government had not been transparent over these issues.



Madzorera said while the vaccine brought new hope for permanent relief, there could only be buy-in from citizens if they were given adequate information and everything was done above board.



“Dissemination of correct information is key to the acceptance of any particular vaccine by the people, in our case the Sinopharm vaccine, at least for now. The current low uptake is due to a lack of information, which buttresses all the conspiracy theories,” he said.



